2 Introduction

Investigate if summer NAO (sNAO) has an effect on body mass of Ovis aries and determine other factors.

2.1 Hypothesis

  • Null - The sNAO has no effect on body mass within the population.
  • Alternative - NAO and sNAO determines weight within the population.

4.2 Creating a summer NAO category.

The difference in Figure 2. justifies creating a new variable sNAO category.

#### lets try to create a summer categorical variable to group by ###
## 28/12/2022

#filter for the summer months with increased NAO variation
summer_filter <- c("June", "July", "August")

### creating a category of sNAO and not sNAO for visualisaton
seasonal_nao_data <- nao_data %>%
  mutate(nao_type = case_when(month %in% summer_filter ~ "summer_NAO", #in summer
                              !month %in% summer_filter ~ "not_summer_NAO")) %>% #not in summer
  group_by(year,nao_type) %>% 
  summarise(mean_nao = mean(NAO))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

6 Generalised linear models (GLMs)

6.1 Transformation before GLMs

Examine casual relationships.

  • Variables of interest.
    • summer NAO
    • year
    • age
    • sex
## A final data transformation brings the variables of interest together.

# predictors, sex, age, nao type  and year.

grp_mass_predictors <- mass_data %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(year, age, sex) %>% #grouping by highest correlated predictors
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(weight)) %>%   #remove NAs
  dplyr::rename(age_yrs = age) %>% #add in units of measure.
  summarise(mean_weight_diff_kg = mean(weight)) # mean weight difference per year
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'age_yrs'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
# join in NAO type data.
grp_mass_pred_NAO <- dplyr::left_join(grp_mass_predictors, seasonal_nao_data,
                                     by = c("year"= "year"))
#view the transformation
head(grp_mass_pred_NAO) %>% kable()

6.3 Creating Models

# predictors - mean_nao 

mod1 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")

# predictors mean nao, and sex
mod2 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao + sex,
              data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
              family = "gaussian")


# predictors mean nao, and sex interacting with age
mod3 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao + age_yrs * sex,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")

# null model for comparison
null_mod <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ 1,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")



# predictors age interaction with sex (added after output analysis)
mod3.1 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ age_yrs + sex,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")


# predictors  age and sex without interaction  (added after output analysis)
mod3.2 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao + sex + age_yrs,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")


# predictors mean nao and  nao_type type
mod4 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao + nao_type,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")

# predictors - sex, age and type- give some interactions
mod5 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao + mean_nao:sex,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")

# predictors - sex, age and type- give some interactions
mod6 <- glm(mean_weight_diff_kg ~ mean_nao + sex:nao_type,
            data = grp_mass_pred_NAO,
            family = "gaussian")

  • coefficients

The sex group male has a significant difference because the p-value is < 0.05. The male group sees an average logit decrease of -13.1 in the response variable weight. It is interesting that the equivalent in females observes an increase of 4.13.

The model provides evidence that male weight is more negatively affected by NAO.

The age_yrs variable has a p-value < 0.05, which suggests age affects the weight response variable. The interaction between sex and age is not significant.

  • Null and residual deviance

There is a large decrease in residual deviance compared to the null deviance suggesting the predictors have influence on weight. A limitation is the residual deviance is high when compared to the residual degrees of freedom.

#re-wrangle the grouped data to include a wider set of variables to investigate random effects.

grp_mass_predictors_v2 <-  mass_data %>% 
  #re_grouping,adding in site and n_babies as factors
  dplyr::group_by( year, age, sex, site = as.factor(site), n_babies = as.factor(n_babies )) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(weight)) %>%   #remove NAs

# number of babies as a random effect

8 Discussion

To conclude, a positive relationship between weight difference and mean NAO has been identified (Figure 9). Sex and age are predictors of weight with males presenting a decrease in response (Figure 7). Figure 13 shows how this relationship correlates higher within the sNAO period.

There is evidence to reject the null hypothesis and claim that NAO is a variable that is linked to weight difference in Oves ares.

However, a single causal relationship between sNAO and weight change is not appropriate.

Year has been estimated as a random effect on weight, but a significant temporal auto correlation is overestimating the relationships. (Figure 23)

Further investigations could include weight transformations (cube roots) to remove negative values and apply different models or adding an age range category.
